{
  "_note": "LT9 — DCL miss OUTPUT-control on top of the LT8 hit-control stack. LT8 proved the input-control miss (class-evade stamp) is frontal-arc only; here the VM ALWAYS connects (the decision callback stamps 0x46..0x4E all 0 for BOTH outcomes), the pre-clamp zeroes the staged debit on a cached MISS ([DCL] ... outcome=forced-miss), and a third managed hook at the result-kind commit 0x205B38 (Strong-static, UNPROVEN live — this test is its proof) flips the committed outcome-kind byte +0x1C0 to 0x06 before the engine's own store ([DCL-KIND] naturalKind -> forcedKind). Damage formula now carries the Mana-Shield guard (dcl.oldDebit > 0) so redirected-to-MP hits keep vanilla staging. PASS = (1) forced misses RENDER as a miss from ANY attack angle — frontal, side AND rear — and against monsters; record EXACTLY what the UI shows ('Miss'/Evaded text, 0-damage popup, or something else — the presentation of a kind-flip after a VM hit is itself an experiment); (2) hits are unchanged from LT8 (LT7-model damage, UI HP drop == [DCL] debit); (3) every executed swing logs a [DCL-KIND] line showing the natural kind and the flip (forcedKind=0x06 decision=miss) or the keep (forcedKind=kept decision=hit); (4) [DCL-HIT] lines now carry ax/ay/af/tx/ty/tf raw position+facing bytes — correlate them with the attack angle. SIDE EFFECTS TO RECORD, NOT NECESSARILY FAILURES: the VM believes it HIT, so counter/reaction triggers, knockback and status procs on a forced miss are expected observables — log what happens. [DCL-KIND-SKIP] at install = AOB guard tripped, feature disabled, whole test moot (report immediately).",
